1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,769
Here's a piece on why QA and testing aren't overhead to be trimmed for AI speed, but the

2
00:00:04,769 --> 00:00:09,266
actual memory of a development department — and if you're feeling pressure to trade

3
00:00:09,266 --> 00:00:13,872
quality process for velocity, the part you'll want most is why the AI era doubles the

4
00:00:13,872 --> 00:00:17,232
stakes, and the five team practices you can start this sprint.

5
00:00:17,232 --> 00:00:22,719
There is a question moving through development departments right now, sometimes spoken,

6
00:00:22,719 --> 00:00:28,080
mostly implied by budget lines: if AI writes more and more of the code, and writes it

7
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:31,548
fast, do we still need all this process around quality?

8
00:00:31,548 --> 00:00:39,558
The reviews, the test suites, the triage meetings, the QA function itself — weren't those mostly there to catch human mistakes?

9
00:00:39,558 --> 00:00:44,477
This talk answers that question, and the answer runs opposite to the instinct.

10
00:00:44,477 --> 00:00:48,072
QA and testing were never mainly about catching mistakes.

11
00:00:48,072 --> 00:00:50,872
Three claims, and the whole talk hangs on them.

12
00:00:50,872 --> 00:00:56,056
First: the test suite is a development department's memory — the one place its hard-won

13
00:00:56,056 --> 00:00:59,333
knowledge is stored in a form that cannot silently rot.

14
00:00:59,333 --> 00:01:04,516
Second: verification is a team dialogue, never the author's monologue — and that is the

15
00:01:04,516 --> 00:01:09,461
cardinal rule of this talk: no work is verified by the one who made it, whether the

16
00:01:09,461 --> 00:01:15,598
author is a developer or a model, because quality is a property of a team, not a virtue of individuals.

17
00:01:15,598 --> 00:01:20,781
Third: in the AI era, where code and even tests can be generated faster than anyone can

18
00:01:20,781 --> 00:01:25,607
read them, review is what turns generated output into warranted knowledge — and a

19
00:01:25,607 --> 00:01:32,280
department that skips it is not saving time; it is accumulating a new kind of debt with an old kind of interest.

20
00:01:32,280 --> 00:01:34,442
This is the third talk in a series.

21
00:01:34,442 --> 00:01:39,880
The first argued that AI belongs in staged pipelines with human checkpoints; the second,

22
00:01:39,880 --> 00:01:44,884
that organizations lose their connective tissue when the assistant answers first.

23
00:01:44,884 --> 00:01:50,136
This one is about where those arguments touch the ground in a development department.

24
00:01:50,136 --> 00:01:52,181
Part one: the suite is the memory.

25
00:01:52,181 --> 00:01:55,550
Start with what a test actually is, stripped of tooling.

26
00:01:55,550 --> 00:01:58,136
A test is a decision that remembers itself.

27
00:01:58,136 --> 00:02:03,309
Somebody once decided that this endpoint must reject a negative amount, that this date

28
00:02:03,309 --> 00:02:08,602
math must survive a leap year, that this timeout must fall back gracefully — and instead

29
00:02:08,602 --> 00:02:13,655
of recording that decision in a document, they recorded it in a form that re-asserts

30
00:02:13,655 --> 00:02:18,888
itself on every commit, forever, against every future colleague and every future model.

31
00:02:18,888 --> 00:02:21,106
Compare the fates of the two forms.

32
00:02:21,106 --> 00:02:26,747
Requirements documents, wiki pages, architecture decks are written once, read seldom, and

33
00:02:26,747 --> 00:02:32,768
drift from the truth the day after publication, because nothing happens when they become wrong.

34
00:02:32,768 --> 00:02:34,606
A test cannot drift silently.

35
00:02:34,606 --> 00:02:41,767
The moment reality disagrees with it, one of them fails loudly, and a human is summoned to decide which is right.

36
00:02:41,767 --> 00:02:50,197
That property — knowledge that defends itself — makes the suite the only documentation in the organization that is guaranteed honest.

37
00:02:50,197 --> 00:02:55,711
Ask any senior engineer how they approach an unfamiliar codebase: read the tests first.

38
00:02:55,711 --> 00:03:01,288
The suite is the fastest truthful map of what a system actually promises — an onboarding

39
00:03:01,288 --> 00:03:06,168
document written by everyone, verified continuously, impossible to embellish.

40
00:03:06,168 --> 00:03:08,906
Now look at what accumulates in its corners.

41
00:03:08,906 --> 00:03:14,010
The fixture with the customer who has two addresses and a name with an apostrophe.

42
00:03:14,010 --> 00:03:18,428
The test for the order placed at midnight on the last day of a quarter.

43
00:03:18,428 --> 00:03:24,216
The regression case for the rounding error that only appears above one million Danish kroner.

44
00:03:24,216 --> 00:03:29,693
That is not test data; that is decades of domain knowledge, crystallized — every strange

45
00:03:29,693 --> 00:03:36,601
truth about the business that someone once learned the hard way, kept alive in a form that bites when violated.

46
00:03:36,601 --> 00:03:38,592
People leave. The fixtures stay.

47
00:03:38,592 --> 00:03:42,245
The memory grows by two mechanisms, and both deserve naming.

48
00:03:42,245 --> 00:03:47,480
The first is that writing a test is doing the understanding: to test anything you must

49
00:03:47,480 --> 00:03:54,420
first say precisely what correct means — inputs, boundaries, failure behavior, the cases nobody put in the ticket.

50
00:03:54,420 --> 00:03:59,778
That act converts a feeling in one head into an artifact a team can inspect and dispute;

51
00:03:59,778 --> 00:04:06,596
when behavior is argued about in a meeting, the healthiest possible outcome is that the argument ends in a test.

52
00:04:06,596 --> 00:04:11,040
The test is the minutes of the meeting — and unlike minutes, it executes.

53
00:04:11,040 --> 00:04:13,641
The second mechanism is that bugs are tuition.

54
00:04:13,641 --> 00:04:18,221
Every production defect is expensive education, and the discipline that separates

55
00:04:18,221 --> 00:04:22,802
learning departments from lucky ones is what happens next: the incident ends as a

56
00:04:22,802 --> 00:04:30,153
regression test plus one written line of why, and the organization acquires scar tissue — it cannot be wounded the same way twice.

57
00:04:30,153 --> 00:04:35,072
Google's engineering culture formalized this as the blameless postmortem, and the point

58
00:04:35,072 --> 00:04:39,822
of blamelessness is not politeness; it is that failures are treated as team learning

59
00:04:39,822 --> 00:04:43,554
events, because that is the only way people surface them honestly.

60
00:04:43,554 --> 00:04:48,474
Departments without this discipline pay the same tuition repeatedly — the same class of

61
00:04:48,474 --> 00:04:53,280
bug returning in a different jacket, re-diagnosed from scratch by whoever is on call.

62
00:04:53,280 --> 00:04:57,259
Part two: quality is a team property, not an individual virtue.

63
00:04:57,259 --> 00:05:02,816
Here is where this talk turns, because everything in part one is routinely undermined by

64
00:05:02,816 --> 00:05:07,868
a single organizational habit: treating quality as an individual responsibility.

65
00:05:07,868 --> 00:05:13,110
It sounds virtuous — every developer tests their own work; the QA engineer down the

66
00:05:13,110 --> 00:05:17,341
corridor owns the quality gate; everyone is personally accountable.

67
00:05:17,341 --> 00:05:21,824
And it quietly guarantees the opposite of everything we just described.

68
00:05:21,824 --> 00:05:29,466
If testing is an individual chore appended to each developer's task, then whatever each test knows stays with its author.

69
00:05:29,466 --> 00:05:35,907
If QA is one person's department, then the end-to-end picture of the system lives in exactly one head.

70
00:05:35,907 --> 00:05:43,296
Individual quality produces individual knowledge — sealed compartments, individually diligent, collectively ignorant.

71
00:05:43,296 --> 00:05:46,046
The oldest rule in the discipline says why.

72
00:05:46,046 --> 00:05:52,185
Glenford Myers wrote it down in The Art of Software Testing in 1979: never verify your own work.

73
00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:57,812
The familiar argument is bias — the same mental model that produced the bug produces the

74
00:05:57,812 --> 00:06:02,992
test that misses it; the author searches for confirmation that it works, a tester

75
00:06:02,992 --> 00:06:08,875
searches for the ways it fails, and those are different searches that find different things.

76
00:06:08,875 --> 00:06:12,648
The bias argument is true. It is also not the cardinal one.

77
00:06:12,648 --> 00:06:20,052
The cardinal argument is this: the moment your work must be verified by someone else, a conversation becomes unavoidable.

78
00:06:20,052 --> 00:06:27,639
The verifier has to ask the most knowledge-productive question in a development department — how is this supposed to behave?

79
00:06:27,639 --> 00:06:32,901
— and you have to answer it, out loud, to a mind that does not share your assumptions.

80
00:06:32,901 --> 00:06:37,001
In that exchange, everything this talk cares about happens at once.

81
00:06:37,001 --> 00:06:39,815
Your tacit understanding is forced into words.

82
00:06:39,815 --> 00:06:45,689
The unstated requirement surfaces where the verifier's model of the problem collides with yours.

83
00:06:45,689 --> 00:06:50,707
The edge case neither of you had written down is discovered in the gap between two

84
00:06:50,707 --> 00:06:54,011
perspectives — before production discovers it for you.

85
00:06:54,011 --> 00:06:59,212
Self-testing is a monologue: the knowledge never has to survive expression to another

86
00:06:59,212 --> 00:07:03,373
human being, so it never becomes shareable, checkable, or teachable.

87
00:07:03,373 --> 00:07:06,432
Independent testing is a dialogue with a deadline.

88
00:07:06,432 --> 00:07:11,629
The previous talk in this series argued that informal knowledge exchange lost its carrier

89
00:07:11,629 --> 00:07:14,608
when the assistant made asking colleagues optional.

90
00:07:14,608 --> 00:07:19,805
See what the test handoff is in that light: it is that exchange with the option removed —

91
00:07:19,805 --> 00:07:25,995
a conversation built into the structure of the work, one that cannot be quietly skipped on a busy Tuesday.

92
00:07:25,995 --> 00:07:31,193
When a department lets developers verify their own work, it is not saving a process step.

93
00:07:31,193 --> 00:07:34,872
It is deleting the last mandatory conversation in its pipeline.

94
00:07:34,872 --> 00:07:39,495
And the dialogue does something deeper than spread knowledge: it secures it.

95
00:07:39,495 --> 00:07:44,909
As long as only its author has exercised a behavior, the organization's grasp of it has a

96
00:07:44,909 --> 00:07:51,479
bus factor of one — the author can resign, forget, or have been wrong from the start, and nobody would know.

97
00:07:51,479 --> 00:07:56,650
The moment a second mind verifies it, the knowledge is duplicated, hardened against a

98
00:07:56,650 --> 00:08:01,273
different model of the problem, and anchored in an artifact both can defend.

99
00:08:01,273 --> 00:08:06,262
Verification is how knowledge changes owner — from the author to the organization.

100
00:08:06,262 --> 00:08:11,433
Until then, a claim only its author has verified is not yet organizational knowledge.

101
00:08:11,433 --> 00:08:13,440
It is a rumor with a commit hash.

102
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:18,573
Follow the logic to its structural conclusion and the team framing stops being a slogan.

103
00:08:18,573 --> 00:08:23,764
If verification must be independent, then quality work is collective by construction: the

104
00:08:23,764 --> 00:08:28,897
suite belongs to the team, not to whoever happened to write each test; review rotates so

105
00:08:28,897 --> 00:08:33,972
no pairing hardens into a private channel; triage happens in a room because the room is

106
00:08:33,972 --> 00:08:39,163
where the who-knows-what map gets refreshed and where a junior learns how a senior probes

107
00:08:39,163 --> 00:08:43,713
a failure; the definition of done is a team artifact, not a personal standard.

108
00:08:43,713 --> 00:08:45,171
None of this is ceremony.

109
00:08:45,171 --> 00:08:52,695
Every quality activity done together is simultaneously a gate and an act of knowledge circulation — the same hour does both jobs.

110
00:08:52,695 --> 00:08:54,912
Done alone, it is cost without memory.

111
00:08:54,912 --> 00:09:00,325
Part three: the AI era, and epistemic debt. Everything so far was true before AI.

112
00:09:00,325 --> 00:09:02,530
Here is why it now matters twice.

113
00:09:02,530 --> 00:09:06,539
The industry's own data tells the story from two directions.

114
00:09:06,539 --> 00:09:12,419
The DORA State of AI-assisted Software Development report — the largest running study of

115
00:09:12,419 --> 00:09:18,366
delivery performance — finds AI adoption correlates with higher throughput and with worse

116
00:09:18,366 --> 00:09:21,774
delivery stability: teams ship more and break more.

117
00:09:21,774 --> 00:09:27,722
And GitClear's analysis of over two hundred million changed lines found that between 2021

118
00:09:27,722 --> 00:09:33,268
and 2024, copy-pasted code rose from about eight to over twelve percent, code churn

119
00:09:33,268 --> 00:09:38,881
nearly doubled, and refactoring collapsed from a quarter of all changes to under ten

120
00:09:38,881 --> 00:09:43,826
percent — the first year on record where duplication outpaced refactoring.

121
00:09:43,826 --> 00:09:46,766
Generation got cheap. Understanding did not.

122
00:09:46,766 --> 00:09:50,040
The gap between the two is landing in production.

123
00:09:50,040 --> 00:09:52,817
Now bring the cardinal rule to the new author.

124
00:09:52,817 --> 00:09:57,585
It is tempting to close the gap by having the model test its own output, and as

125
00:09:57,585 --> 00:10:01,629
scaffolding it should — generated tests are excellent raw material.

126
00:10:01,629 --> 00:10:07,182
But watch what happens when nobody reviews them, because the failure hides inside good news.

127
00:10:07,182 --> 00:10:13,520
The model writes the code; the model writes tests that assert what the code already does; the tests pass.

128
00:10:13,520 --> 00:10:20,643
A test that restates its own implementation is not evidence — it is a self-fulfilling prophecy with a green checkmark.

129
00:10:20,643 --> 00:10:25,894
The suite fills with assertions nobody argued for, the dashboard glows, and the warrant

130
00:10:25,894 --> 00:10:29,576
everyone assumes must exist was never manufactured by anyone.

131
00:10:29,576 --> 00:10:37,423
This is the oldest distinction in the theory of knowledge, wearing engineering clothes: producing an answer is not justifying one.

132
00:10:37,423 --> 00:10:38,751
Output is not warrant.

133
00:10:38,751 --> 00:10:44,123
Capability produces candidates; warrant is what makes a candidate safe to act on — and in

134
00:10:44,123 --> 00:10:52,272
this story warrant comes from exactly one place: a mind independent of the author deciding that the assertion is the right one to make.

135
00:10:52,272 --> 00:10:57,361
There is a name for what accumulates when that step is skipped: epistemic debt — the

136
00:10:57,361 --> 00:11:02,148
growing distance between what the system relies on and what is still warranted.

137
00:11:02,148 --> 00:11:07,298
It compounds quietly, because every unreviewed generated test adds another assumption

138
00:11:07,298 --> 00:11:13,902
nobody owns, and it is repaid the way all debt is repaid: later, with interest, at the worst possible moment.

139
00:11:13,902 --> 00:11:19,840
Test review — the team reading the generated assertions and asking, is this actually what we mean?

140
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:22,869
— is not process overhead on top of the real work.

141
00:11:22,869 --> 00:11:28,261
It is the step that converts generated candidates into justified claims: the department's

142
00:11:28,261 --> 00:11:32,684
defense against paying interest on green builds it never actually earned.

143
00:11:32,684 --> 00:11:35,532
This was never a new rule for a new technology.

144
00:11:35,532 --> 00:11:40,379
It is Myers' rule, applied to a new kind of author — one that produces plausible

145
00:11:40,379 --> 00:11:45,408
verification of its own work at industrial speed, and holds no employment contract.

146
00:11:45,408 --> 00:11:48,771
Reframe, finally, what the reviewed suite buys you: speed.

147
00:11:48,771 --> 00:11:53,583
The department with a trustworthy regression suite is the one that can accept large

148
00:11:53,583 --> 00:11:59,148
AI-generated changes quickly, because the net is strong enough to catch what the reading missed.

149
00:11:59,148 --> 00:12:04,250
Tests are not the brakes that slow the car; they are the brakes that let you drive fast.

150
00:12:04,250 --> 00:12:09,294
Departments that deleted their quality process to go faster with AI chose to drive fast

151
00:12:09,294 --> 00:12:14,976
without brakes — and the DORA stability numbers are what that choice looks like at industry scale.

152
00:12:14,976 --> 00:12:21,993
Now, in fairness, the honest failure modes — five concessions, so this survives your most skeptical colleague.

153
00:12:21,993 --> 00:12:27,288
Coverage worship: one hundred percent coverage of tests that assert nothing anchors

154
00:12:27,288 --> 00:12:33,412
nothing — coverage measures execution, not knowledge; review the assertions, not the percentage.

155
00:12:33,412 --> 00:12:41,132
Rubber-stamp review: an approval in forty seconds transfers no judgment; if review is theater, it is cost without memory.

156
00:12:41,132 --> 00:12:49,680
Gatekeeping nostalgia: QA as a toll booth deserved its bad name — the case here is for QA as a learning organ, not a department of no.

157
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:54,981
Outsourcing the organ: handing all testing to the cheapest external provider does not

158
00:12:54,981 --> 00:13:02,341
outsource a task, it outsources the learning; a department can hollow itself this way while its dashboards stay green.

159
00:13:02,341 --> 00:13:07,580
And the newest one, quality as individual scorecard: the moment defect counts become

160
00:13:07,580 --> 00:13:13,505
personal KPIs, people stop surfacing failures, the dialogue dies, and the memory stops growing.

161
00:13:13,505 --> 00:13:18,744
Measure teams, never heads — blamelessness is not softness; it is a memory strategy.

162
00:13:18,744 --> 00:13:20,479
So what do you actually do?

163
00:13:20,479 --> 00:13:27,420
The program is small enough to start this sprint, and every item is a team practice, not an individual duty.

164
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:33,718
Every bug that reaches production ends its life as a regression test plus one written line of why.

165
00:13:33,718 --> 00:13:39,309
Review AI-generated code and its AI-generated tests together — senior and junior at the

166
00:13:39,309 --> 00:13:44,450
same screen, asking whether the assertions say what the team means; that hour is

167
00:13:44,450 --> 00:13:48,820
simultaneously the quality gate, the classroom, and the map-refresh.

168
00:13:48,820 --> 00:13:51,520
Let disputes about behavior end in a test.

169
00:13:51,520 --> 00:13:56,661
Rotate test and review ownership so no knowledge hardens into a private channel.

170
00:13:56,661 --> 00:14:03,216
And make the cardinal rule written policy: nothing ships verified only by its author — human or model.

171
00:14:03,216 --> 00:14:08,385
Then watch three numbers, and put them on a team dashboard, never a personal one.

172
00:14:08,385 --> 00:14:12,852
Same-bug recurrence — the direct measurement of organizational memory.

173
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:18,020
Time-to-reproduce — a live reading of whether the who-knows-what map still works.

174
00:14:18,020 --> 00:14:24,912
And regression tests added per incident — whether tuition is being converted into knowledge, or merely paid.

175
00:14:24,912 --> 00:14:27,736
And what remains, when you strip it all down?

176
00:14:27,736 --> 00:14:32,506
A development department's real asset was never this quarter's feature list.

177
00:14:32,506 --> 00:14:40,476
It is the accumulated, hard-won model of the domain — every rule, every exception, every way the system has ever surprised you.

178
00:14:40,476 --> 00:14:45,935
That asset has exactly one home that does not evaporate when a person resigns, does not

179
00:14:45,935 --> 00:14:54,094
drift when a document ages, and does not depend on a model's context window: the test suite, and the team dialogue that builds it.

180
00:14:54,094 --> 00:14:59,428
The code, increasingly, anyone can generate — and unreviewed, it is only a candidate.

181
00:14:59,428 --> 00:15:07,147
What your tests know, because your team argued it into them together — that is warranted, that is owned, and that is yours.

182
00:15:07,147 --> 00:15:09,595
Quality was never an individual virtue.

183
00:15:09,595 --> 00:15:13,737
It is how a team thinks together, and what a department remembers.

184
00:15:13,737 --> 00:15:19,824
Anchor it — and guard the door with the cardinal rule: nothing enters on its author's word alone.

185
00:15:19,824 --> 00:15:22,361
A note on the research behind this talk.

186
00:15:22,361 --> 00:15:28,007
It draws on the DORA State of AI-assisted Software Development report; GitClear's AI code

187
00:15:28,007 --> 00:15:33,271
quality research, covering two hundred eleven million lines analyzed; Google's Site

188
00:15:33,271 --> 00:15:38,853
Reliability Engineering book and its chapter on postmortem culture; Microsoft's study of

189
00:15:38,853 --> 00:15:44,118
collaboration networks published in Nature Human Behaviour; reporting on the junior

190
00:15:44,118 --> 00:15:52,238
developer pipeline crisis; and Glenford Myers, The Art of Software Testing, 1979, the classic statement of testing independence.

191
00:15:52,238 --> 00:15:56,424
This presentation was produced end to end by Fluent Agents Studio.

192
00:15:56,424 --> 00:16:03,408
That's the readout — now go make sure the thing your team knows lives somewhere that can't quit, drift, or forget.
